Introduction¶

This dataset contains information about a lot of movies produced and released in a period of years ( from 1960 to 2015 ) along with some attributes to each movie like the actors , the genre , the budget , the producing companies , the revenue , the vote average ...etc.¶

In this dataset , we want to investigate its properties and try to derive some relationships between its attributes.¶

Mainly this investigation aims to answer the following questions :¶

  1. What production companies produced the highst amount of movies ?
  2. What are the factors that leads to high vote results for the movies ?
  3. Do people love certain genres in movies ?
  4. Which actors have the highest frequency in participation in movies ?
  5. What directors produced the highst amount of movies and what are their ratings ?

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

  • ### Research Question 1 (What production companies produced the highst number of movies in a certain period)

From above ,we notice that the min release year in the dataset is 1960 and the max year is 2015 . One possible approach that we introduce is to find the solution for our question is to divide the release years into 5 periods ( 1960 - 1970 , 1970 -1980 , 1980 - 1990 , 1990 - 2000 , 2000 - 2015 ).

In [73]:
#Create the seperation intervals for the periods
SeperateBins = [1960,1970,1980,1990,2000,2015]
In [74]:
#We use cut function to seperate the time intervals as specified 
YearsCategories = pa.cut(df.release_year,SeperateBins,labels=['60th','70th','80th','90th','21century'],include_lowest=True)
In [75]:
#we will add a new column to the dataset which is the category of the time interval
df['period_category']=YearsCategories
In [76]:
#Grouping by the new column 'period_category'
df_YearsGrouped = df.groupby('period_category')
In [77]:
#looping on the groups that are produced from the group by function and each group we will do our processing
for group_name, df_group in df_YearsGrouped:
    dictionary = {}   #initialize a dictionary to add the production companies with their repetition
    
    for row_index, row in df_group.iterrows():   #iterate over the rows of each group 
        productionCompanies = row['production_companies'].split('|')  #because there are several production comapnies participating in each movie , so we will split those companies by using split function
        for company in productionCompanies :  #adding a new company to the dictionary or if it is found then increase its value by one
            if company in dictionary :
                oldValue = dictionary[company]
                newValue=oldValue+1
                dictionary[company] = newValue
            else :
                dictionary[company]=1
                
    a=dict(sorted(dictionary.items(), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)[:10]).items()  #sort the companies in the dictionary and get the highst 10 companies 
    
    print ("The Top Ten Production companies in the {}".format(group_name))
    print (a)
    
    x, y = zip(*a) # unpack a list of pairs into two tuples
    plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 8})    #we will specifiy the prop. of the Plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,5))
    plt.bar(x, y,width=0.3)
    plt.xticks(rotation='vertical')
    plt.xlabel("Production Companies")
    plt.ylabel("Number of movies")
    plt.title("Top ten production companies in Participation in Movies production in the {}".format(group_name))
   
    
    plt.show() # showing the plot
    print ("..................................................................................................................")

model = sm.OLS(df.vote_average,sm.add_constant(df.runtime))

Color = ny.array([.5, .6, .7])
#scatter plot data

  • ### Research Question 4 (Relation between the Genre and the movies (average vote result & count of movies))

We will discuss if the Genre of the movie is affecting the average vote result of the movie in the same time intervals that we grouped the dataset into in the previous questions.

Since each movie can belong to several genres , we want to make a list of distinct genres , and then we can iterate over the rows to count the genres and calculate the average score .

Because the count of votes is not consistent over the movies , we want to calculate a weighted average vote result depending on the number of the votes , so we will assume a weighting function to calculate a weighted result , just to distinct the movies that have higher count of votes .

The Function is :

$$WA = CA * log (VC)$$

where :

$WA : Weighted Average$

$CA : Calculated Average$

$VC : Votes Count$

In [84]:
import math # import math to use thhe log function

for group_name, df_group in df_YearsGrouped : #iterate over each group in the time intervals as before
    listOfGenres =[] #list to add the distinct genre types
    GenresDict = {} #dictionary to addthe genre along with the value of repetition
    
    for row_index, row in df_group.iterrows() : #iterate over each row to get the genre types
        genres = row['genres'].split('|')  #use split function to split the genres
        for genre in genres :
            if genre in listOfGenres :
                #do nothing we want distinct values of genres in the list
                continue
            else :
                #add the genre to the list
                listOfGenres.append(genre)
    
    for genre in listOfGenres :  #iterate over the genres in the list and calculate their repetition
        movie_counter=0   #initialize a movies counter
        WA=0  #initilaize a weighted average variable
        
        for row_index, row in df_group.iterrows() :  #iterate over the rows again to calculate the number of movies along with the weighted average vote result
            if genre in row['genres'] :  #if the genre is in the row 
                movie_counter=movie_counter+1   #increment the movies counter
                WA = WA + (row['vote_average'] * math.log(row['vote_count'])) #calculate the accumulative weighted average
    
        tupleOfValues=(WA,movie_counter)  #create a tuple to put the weighted average with the movie counter as a value in the dictionary
        GenresDict[genre]=tupleOfValues  # assign the tuple as a value in the dictionary
        
    x=list(GenresDict.keys())
    y=list(GenresDict.values())
    cumulativeVotesAverage, moviesCount = zip(*y)  #unpack the tuple of values
    
    print ("The  {}".format(group_name)+" Group")
    plt.style.use('seaborn')
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
    plt.xlabel("Genre")
    plt.xticks(rotation='vertical')
    plt.ylabel("cumulative Votes Average")
    plt.title("Relation between Genre and cumulative average Weighted votes in {}".format(group_name))
    
  
    sc=plt.scatter(x,cumulativeVotesAverage,s=moviesCount)  #we will print a bubble chart 
    plt.legend(*sc.legend_elements("sizes",num=6),title="Movies Count")  #The size of bubble indicates the count of movies in this genre
    plt.show()
   
    print (".........................................................................................................")

  • ### Research Question 5 (Who is the most successfull director with regard to number of movies and votes average)

We will group our dataset by the same previous time interval and by the director.

In [85]:
for group_name, df_group in df_YearsGrouped :   #here we will iterate over the groups that are grouped by the period and regroup them with the director also 
    print (group_name)
    
    #grouping by the director , and then getting the count of movies and the sum of the average votes , and selecting the largest 5 directors in movies count
    df1 = df_group.groupby('director').agg({'original_title':'count', 'vote_average': 'sum'}).reset_index().nlargest(5,columns='original_title')
    
    df2 = pa.DataFrame(data=df1)  #forming a new dataframe of the previous output
    
    df2.rename(columns={'original_title':'countOfMovies'},inplace=True)  #rename the column 'original_title' to 'countOfMovies' since it is aggregated on the count
    
    df2['new_VoteAvergare']=df2['vote_average']/df2['countOfMovies']  #we make a new column in the dataframe which is the result of dividing the sum of the Average vote result with the movies count
    
    x=df2['director']
    y=df2['countOfMovies']
    z=df2['new_VoteAvergare']
    
  

    opacity = 0.8
    bar_width = 0.4

    plt.xlabel('directors')
    plt.ylabel('movies count')
    plt.title("Relation between director and number of movies and the average vote result of them ")

    
    chart = plt.bar(x,y, bar_width, align='center', alpha=opacity, color='b')
    

    # Add average vote results above the bar graph for indication
    for index,rect in enumerate(chart) :
        length = rect.get_height()
        plt.text(x = index ,y = length ,s='votesAvg='+str(round(z.iloc[index],3)) ,ha='center', va='bottom')

    plt.show()

  • in the 60th : Roger Corman was the highest director in the number of movies , however he was nearly the worst in the votes result , while Billy Wilder and Blake Edwards have an opposite case ( low number of movies and high vote result ) .
  • in the 70th : There are 4 directors who share the same number of movies and also their vote result is very near , but Woody Allen who had the highest vote result .
  • in the 80th : It seems that Woody Allen is still on the top in the count of movies , also his vote result is very good , but John Carpenter exceeds him in the vote result .
  • in the 90th : As in the previous period , Woody Allen is still on the top in the count of movies , while Oliver Stone and Clint Eastwood are the most successfull in the votes result .
  • in the 21century : Steven Soderbergh has the highest count of movies but with a relativly low vote result , whilethe contrast happened with Clint Easwtood which had the lowest count of movies and highest vote result .

  • ### Conclusions

Here in this section , we will summarize our analysis and conclude our results that are based upon our analysis in the previous sections

  • #### Overview of the dataset
  • This dataset is called TDMB dataset , it has data related to movies and some of their attributes from 1960 untill 2015 .
  • The dataset has initilally 10866 rows and 21 columns .
  • The information in this dataset is related to the movie along with its release date , production companies , cast , director votes result , revenue , budget ...etc.
  • #### Summary for the data cleaning process
  • We cleaned our data by removing duplicate rows if any .
  • We deleted the rows that contain null values
  • We dropped the columns that we we don't need in our analysis like the id , homepage , tagline and others
  • we dropped columns like budget and revenue because nearly more than 60 % of the total data in them were zero values ( means they are unknown ) so it is some sort of biased data , and Our approach was to measure the success of the movie by measuring its votes count and votes average result .
  • #### Limitations of the dataset
  • Some columns like Genres and cast have multiple values in each cell .
  • Some fields have some unrecognized characters in its values .
  • Columns as budget and revenue have biased values in more than 60% of their data ( either zero or very small unreasonable value like 2 or 3 ) , so it was better to collect this data properly to have better analysis in this part .
  • It would had been better if we had the values in the Genres column a single value i.e. to put the main genre of the movie only in the genres column , so that to have clear insights about the trends of the genres in each time interval and what genres does people like the most .
  • #### Summary of analysis
  • In our Approach we mainly divide the dataset into 5 different intervals according to the release year , either in the 60th or 70th or 80th or 90th or the 21century , we aimed to find changes among number of movies , genres of movies and production companies all over these passing years .
